O God! Thou art my God alone;
When night descends and hope has flown,
I turn my face to find Your gaze,
A lantern through the shadowed haze.
No crown, no scepter, and no throne,
Could trade the love You’ve always shown;
Within the silence, I am grown—
A seed of faith, by mercy sown.
O God! Thou art my God alone;
With every breath, I am Your own.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the amber dusk before it flees;
let petals tumble where you miss,
and laughter ripple through the trees.
Your slippers tap on cobblestones,
a dance beneath the city’s sigh;
the world belongs to those who own
the mischief glimmer in their eye.
So press your lips to fleeting hours,
sow chaos with a blushing grin;
for every rule that you devour
another night will soon begin.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the rain before it falls;
let wonder slip between the mist
and echo down the halls.
With tangled hair and open hands,
you chase the thunder’s tune;
your laughter, wild, unmapped, expands
beneath a reckless moon.
So plant your lips on fleeting things—
a shadow, breeze, or sigh;
for every kiss the nighttime brings,
new dreams are born to fly.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the wild horizon’s edge;
let secrets blossom in your bliss
and promise what you pledge.
Chase the daisy’s fleeting shade,
tie sunlight to your shoes;
let every rule be gently swayed,
and mischief be your muse.
Sweet daring in your eyes alight,
you wander, bold and free;
a comet streaking through the night,
an anthem meant to be.

Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;
A tender echo lingers in the hall,
Where laughter once did tremble, bright and coy,
And sunlight danced upon the plastered wall.
Now silence fills the cradle and the air,
A hush that aches in marrow and in mind;
Yet love endures, a torch I cannot bear,
Still burning where our fates are intertwined.
Go softly, spirit, on the wind’s employ;
Farewell, sweet child of my right hand, and joy.
